The [Belarusians](/Belarusian_language) ( [Belarusian](/Belarusian_language): беларусы, [romanized](/Romanization_of_Belarusian): *biełarusy* [&#91;bʲeɫaˈrusɨ&#93;](/Help:IPA/Belarusian)) represent a distinct [East Slavic](/East_Slavs) [ethnic group](/Ethnic_group) whose ancestral lands are primarily within the modern borders of [Belarus](/Belarus). They are characterized by their native use of the [Belarusian language](/Belarusian_language), itself an [East Slavic language](/East_Slavic_language), though the complexities of history have significantly shaped their linguistic landscape. Globally, the number of individuals identifying with Belarusian ethnicity surpasses 9 million, a testament to a diaspora forged through centuries of shifting borders, political upheavals, and economic migrations.

Within [Belarus](/Belarus) itself, approximately 7.99 million Belarusians form the overwhelming majority of the nation's population, anchoring the cultural and demographic core of the group. However, the narrative of the Belarusian people extends far beyond these national confines. Significant concentrations of Belarusians can be found in the [United States](/United_States), with estimates ranging from 155,000 to as high as 600,000 individuals claiming Belarusian ancestry, and in [Russia](/Russia), where over half a million Belarusians reside. These communities, along with others scattered across the globe, reflect a history of continuous movement and adaptation. The predominant religious affiliation among Belarusians is [Eastern Orthodoxy](/Eastern_Orthodoxy), specifically through the [Belarusian Orthodox Church](/Belarusian_Orthodox_Church), which serves as a vital cultural and spiritual touchstone for many, though other Christian denominations and a growing secular population also form part of the diverse fabric of Belarusian identity.

This overview, while concise, merely scratches the surface of an ethnic group whose identity has been forged in the crucible of empires, linguistic shifts, and profound societal transformations. To truly grasp the Belarusian experience is to delve into a story of resilience, cultural preservation, and a persistent, often understated, struggle for self-definition against a backdrop of geopolitical flux.

